---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="wright-kit · Ray Weiss"
  description="wright-kit is a wargame construction kit. Local-first tools for digitizing hex maps and building orders of battle, working in plain JSON files you own. MIT licensed, no commercial-rights gating."
  colophon={{ sheet: 'IV.A', edition: '2026.07' }}
>
  <div
    slot="sheet-id"
    class="sheet-id"
    aria-label="Sheet identification"
  >
    <div class="plate">
      <span class="num">PL. IV.A</span> wright-kit · Wargame Construction Kit
    </div>
    <div class="edition">Edition 2026.07 · Brooklyn, NY</div>
  </div>

  <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl">
    <header class="hero">
      <img
        src="/counter-rw.svg"
        alt="Ray Weiss unit counter"
        class="counter"
        width="96"
        height="72"
      />
      <div>
        <h1>wright-kit</h1>
        <p class="dek">A wargame construction kit.</p>
        <div class="slug" aria-label="Identification">
          <span><strong>UNIT</strong> RW / 26</span>
          <span class="sep">/</span>
          <span><strong>TYPE</strong> Construction kit</span>
          <span class="sep">/</span>
          <span><strong>LICENSE</strong> MIT</span>
          <span class="sep">/</span>
          <span><strong>FORMAT</strong> Plain JSON</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </header>

    <div class="bio">
      <p>
        wright-kit is the set of tools I use to build digital wargames. Everything is
        local-first: the tools run on your machine, and the work lives in plain JSON files
        you own and can read. The kit is MIT licensed with no commercial-rights gating. A
        game you build with it is yours, including one you sell.
      </p>
    </div>

    <section aria-labelledby="pillars">
      <div class="section-head">
        <h2 class="section-label" id="pillars">
          <span class="pl">PL. IV.A</span>The three pillars
        </h2>
        <span class="section-count">03 entries ——</span>
      </div>
      <ol class="infra-list">
        <li>
          <div class="infra-meta">
            <span
              ><span class="dot live"></span><span class="k">Status</span><span class="v"
                >Public</span
              ></span
            >
            <span><span class="k">Tools</span><span class="v">hexwright · wargame-map-parser</span></span>
            <span><span class="k">Output</span><span class="v">hexgrid JSON</span></span>
          </div>
          <span class="infra-title">Digitize</span>
          <p class="infra-desc">
            Turn a printed map into data. <a href="https://github.com/lerugray/hexwright"
            >hexwright</a> is a hex-map editor for assigning terrain, hexsides, and features
            by hand, where the judgment calls live. wargame-map-parser reads a scanned map
            and produces a first pass for hexwright to refine. The output is one hexgrid
            file that any engine can consume.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <div class="infra-meta">
            <span
              ><span class="dot live"></span><span class="k">Status</span><span class="v"
                >Public</span
              ></span
            >
            <span><span class="k">Tool</span><span class="v">musterwright</span></span>
            <span><span class="k">Output</span><span class="v">force-layer JSON</span></span>
          </div>
          <span class="infra-title">Muster</span>
          <p class="infra-desc">
            Build the order of battle. <a href="https://github.com/lerugray/musterwright"
            >musterwright</a> handles unit rosters, factor sets, and setup positions, and it
            follows hexwright's conventions, so the force layer and the map layer speak the
            same format.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <div class="infra-meta">
            <span
              ><span class="k">Status</span><span class="v">In design</span></span
            >
            <span><span class="k">Scope</span><span class="v">Art · export</span></span>
          </div>
          <span class="infra-title">Publish</span>
          <p class="infra-desc">
            The art and export layer: turning a digitized map and muster into counters,
            printable sheets, and a playable module. This pillar is in design and has not
            shipped. The first two pillars work today; this one is being shaped by the
            commission work that uses them.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </section>

    <section aria-labelledby="repositories" class="mt-16">
      <div class="section-head">
        <h2 class="section-label" id="repositories">
          <span class="pl">PL. IV.A</span>Repositories
        </h2>
      </div>
      <div class="prose-body mt-6">
        <p>
          The umbrella repo is
          <a href="https://github.com/lerugray/wright-kit">github.com/lerugray/wright-kit</a>.
          It holds the kit's conventions and points at the tools:
          <a href="https://github.com/lerugray/hexwright">github.com/lerugray/hexwright</a>
          for the map layer and
          <a href="https://github.com/lerugray/musterwright">github.com/lerugray/musterwright</a>
          for the force layer. Each tool stands alone; the kit is the shared file format
          between them.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <div class="hex-rule" aria-hidden="true">
      <img src="/hex-ornament.svg" alt="" width="96" height="32" />
    </div>

    <aside class="featured" aria-labelledby="commissions">
      <span class="section-label" id="commissions">Proof of work</span>
      <h3>These tools built these commissions</h3>
      <p class="desc">
        The commissioned digital modules on this site, Napoleon at Bay, Flattop, Paths of
        Glory, and For the People, were built with wright-kit. If you want a finished module
        rather than the tools, commissions are open.
      </p>
      <a href="/wargame-modules" class="cta">See the wargame modules &rarr;</a>
    </aside>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
